5. Error
The error can occur while choosing the correct hypothesis based on the statistical tests. Two types of errors are Type I and Type II error.
This kind of error occurs when we reject the null hypothesis even if it is true. It is equivalent to a false positive conclusion. The probability
of type I error is given by the value of , level of significance

Type II Error
This kind of error occurs when we fail to reject the null hypothesis even if it is wrong. It is equivalent to a false negative conclusion. The
probability of type II error is given by the value of Beta.

5.1 Power of Hypothesis Test

The probability of correctly rejecting a false null hypothesis is defined as the Power of a test. It is calculated as 1-β . It is the probability of
avoiding the type II error. The power of the test lies between 0 to 1. The value close to 1 indicates that the test is able to reject the false null
hypothesis correctly


